WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Okay, let me start with just this announcement.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:20.000
My name is Joe Manier of the Southern, and my mic, the Pierre-Choyan.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
A Southern oral history program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:29.000
I'm in New York City and Midtown, or I guess lower Midtown or...

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.000
Yes, this is West Side. West...

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Well, the Flatiron District, I think it's for these on the east side.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Technically a little east of us.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:49.000
I'm with videographer John Bishop, and we are here to do an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:56.000
which is a joint undertaking of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:08.000
And we're just delighted and very honored today to be with Ms. Gloria Hayes' Danridge to talk about all of the work Ms. Danridge that you did and have done over the years in the movement.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
So thank you very much for coming to sit down with us today. We appreciate it.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Let me, I think in our hour, hour and a half that we can spend together day in conversation.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:25.000
I thought I would start just having to talk a little bit about your experience of that Howard, where you enrolled in 1938, I think.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:34.000
Yes. I went to Howard. My cousins had been there before me, and so it was kind of like...

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:45.000
I was young, I think I was like fairly 16. And for me, it was comfortable knowing my cousins, you know, I come up with for there.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:57.000
But I went to Howard, and I think that first year, they said I was shy, but I think it was just a lot going on, and I come from a small town, my first time away from home.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:06.000
But it worked out well in terms of friendships, and then my family knew people in Washington, they had children there.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:15.000
I happened to have gone there when they had some really great minds, and I get...

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:21.000
I don't, I have no sense of what they would be now, but then we're considered very radical.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:32.000
And, you know, they published Franklin Frazier, and I was a tripping class because he thought I was too shy, naive.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:39.000
And he was always explaining his wrong to your comments to me and embarrassing me in front of the class.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:46.000
But anyhow, and Rayford Logan, so it was a good time, and we did...

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:54.000
My first demonstration really was there, first against the university because of a curve views and things.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:59.000
And secondly, there...

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:07.000
And I'm a little confused about what organizations started at, but we did some demonstrations.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:15.000
I think against Woolworths, probably in my junior year.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:29.000
So I went through that, and came out and graduated, worked in the government, took a government exam, worked in the government for a couple of years.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:34.000
Now, I want to ask a little bit more about your how it years.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:41.000
You have written that you've protested at Woolworths, and I think that was picketing rather than...

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:45.000
Oh, yes, no, it was picketing.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:53.000
But you... I'm really interested in how your perspective was emerging as a young adult in those years on.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:03.000
And you've also mentioned your protest on campus over curfews, which was kind of related to the gender notion of women's rules on campus.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
That's true, it's true and right.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.000
It was, it was, yeah.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:15.000
And what was your sense of the world you wanted to create the world you wanted for yourself as a woman as an African-American?

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:19.000
I don't think I thought of creating a world. I think I was just passing through it.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:25.000
I knew I had to make the craze, you know, I had friendships there.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:36.000
I think that it was other people around me that convinced me to go on these demonstrations of picketing.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:39.000
And I went along.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.000
Because even the movement people were writing me saying, is this...

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:49.000
Are you sure you're the same, very shy, you know, girl woman that was at...

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:51.000
Are you sure that's who you are?

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:56.000
And so I guess I've been projecting, probably was.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:03.000
Because when I... The first press conference, when they're outside press can, they had pushed me out to do my eyes.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:12.000
And the only reason why I did it was because I was the only one there that they said they wanted one voice through which to speak.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:17.000
But I had a good time at Howard and I learned a lot.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:25.000
I think because these professors were radical, you know, that came through their lectures.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:32.000
E. Franklin Frazier was really against what he called the Black Dwarfs, where I see it.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:45.000
And some of those people... Some of those models, you know, I had come across with my family and their relationships in various towns across the East Coast.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:49.000
Sure. Let me ask what I want to ask about your family.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:55.000
And if you could situate your family in Cambridge, I know that's a long story.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:00.000
No, it's not a long story, but I...

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:10.000
Well, I guess actually, although I wasn't raised that way, I guess they were in terms of the Black community, the first family in Cambridge.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:16.000
My grandfather had been on the City Council for years.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:21.000
He wasn't the first Black man. I think there were two other Black people that had been in the City Council.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:24.000
And he was the third.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:29.000
We didn't really know until my cousin's not. We were married.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:33.000
It had children that we were supposed to have been wealthy.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:39.000
I can imagine going downtown and he was segregated and saying, oh, I don't know which sweat he couldn't try at home.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:43.000
I don't know. I like that sweater, but we can't afford it.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:48.000
And the clerk's saying to me, why don't you go home and ask your parents if you can afford it?

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:51.000
Because I think they knew better than he did.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:58.000
And because we were in business, you had to speak to everybody or every sports or every street.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.000
And it became almost automatic.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:08.000
My grandfather was not particularly religious, but he gave money and land and stopped to the church.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:24.000
My grandmother, in the winter because we had seasonal workers or seasonal work rather, then the packing companies would send food out in the red cross, all segregated with send whatever clothing they had.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:33.000
And the grandmother would distribute that sometimes by going out into the poor communities and sometimes from our house.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:44.000
I think we mainly were in the family. Most of the family houses were within a block of each other and you ran back and forth.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:52.000
My grandfather was in system that you come back and help the town and the community.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
And I think most of us did.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
Yeah, you moved back after that.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
Come and join me mentioned and family.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:09.000
Can you describe the basic arrangements in Cambridge, racial geography of Cambridge?

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:12.000
It was in the late 50s.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:17.000
It had been, it was totally segregated.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:24.000
The shopping, there was one room reserved in the hospital, one maternity room.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:29.000
And of course, if they got overloaded with white people, then that went.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:33.000
And so you had to be in all.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:39.000
I think they used my grandfather for, you know, should you give this person credit.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:47.000
And in terms, he got a lot of people out of the Merlin Pena Tentry and the J.O.'s and stuff.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:55.000
Even though he sent on the council when they had their annual banquet,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.000
they would infuriate my grandmother.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
They would bring the meal out to him.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
Because he was not allowed to join them.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
Don't join them, that's right.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
So in that respect, I was, and that's true of Washington too.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:14.000
So that was true my life, however, within that framework.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:23.000
And because I guess we were restricted to one ward, then your daily life was within the confines of that.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:31.000
People that had to go outside of that bubble and work, that was a different thing.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:40.000
I just probably fully realized some of that when I just read the book, The Help,

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.000
out of Mississippi during the 60s.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
And it didn't occur to me.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:50.000
It occurred to me that they didn't treat, may not treat their health well.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.000
It didn't occur to me that they would have separate bathrooms.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.000
I mean, I just did not imagine that.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:59.000
When I read it, I believed it.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
But I did not conceive of that.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:07.000
I think Black folks in that town, and people wonder why Cambridge.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:14.000
But I think their history there, they were, and I don't understand this at all.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:20.000
My grandfather was in the census when he was 12 years old, was in school.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:23.000
And I was told where, and they said, in school.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
But they were also slaves there.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:31.000
So there seemed to be a combination of slave, how I, you know, I don't understand that.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:40.000
I know that during a movement, very elderly people told me that at one time people in Cambridge intermarried.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.000
And then something happened.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.000
It was a total separation.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
I don't know whether anything to do with the Civil War or whatever.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:53.000
But at that time, I'm sorry now I wasn't having these conversations with the older people by family,

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
but I didn't care at that point.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:02.000
So I think I grew up probably in a protective atmosphere,

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
although knowing that all of that was going on.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:09.000
And the foundry, yeah, dividing white and black Cambridge and...

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
It was in the charter.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
Yep, and was race street.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:15.000
Yes.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
And I have read that...

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
And until the movement that didn't occur to me.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:25.000
I think the people that came and started saying, the street, you can't go beyond race, it's called race street.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
And I thought, well, yeah, that's true.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:32.000
I always thought, because they used to have, uh, sookies and things, right, racing up and down.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
Right. Right.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:40.000
The black community in Cambridge around 1960, I think it was about 4,000 people.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:49.000
And at that time, I wonder if you recall one of the aspects of segregation in Cambridge

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:56.000
that would be so terribly consequential for your family was the health care and opportunities for health care.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
Oh, yes, and I think so.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:02.000
And the doctors did not have privilege, but doctors did not have privileges.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.000
I mean, hospital privileges.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:08.000
But your father and your uncle, I'm thinking about it.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:13.000
My father had a drug store.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:18.000
My cousin, Carol, was a doctor.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
But he didn't have hospital privileges.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:26.000
If he did, it must have been the late after I was grown.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:29.000
But I know that that was an issue.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:33.000
I think the doctor that came in after him did, and that was a big thing.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:39.000
Oh, you can take your hospital, you don't have to go through another doctor.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:47.000
The doctors, they had separate white doctors, they had separate waiting rooms for you.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:53.000
Most of the time in our family, we went to Baltimore to the Provident Hospital there.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.000
My father had started out there.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
He used to be the drugist's crops.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:03.000
And I think Carol did his internship there.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
But usually we try to get the Provident.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:09.000
Some people in their family went to John Hopkins, but the thing was Hopkins at that time.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:13.000
And I guess the book on Henry at Locke's, which I have not read,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:19.000
probably proves that because some of us in the family just thought they were using glasses any pigs.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:23.000
They too had separate medical facilities.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:26.000
When did your father have his heart attack?

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.000
I don't know. I think now he's rest sometimes in his 50s.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
I'm very bad with years.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:35.000
But he did, but no, but he couldn't not go to the hospital.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:42.000
Because I guess of whatever kind of respect they had for my grandfather,

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:47.000
one of the white doctors came to the hospital.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:53.000
We wanted to move him to Provident Hospital, but by that time it was too late.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.000
But he worked very hard to 12 and 1 o'clock.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:06.000
Not only the prescriptions, but patent medicines and a full range of, I guess, like to any of these stuff.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.000
And the soda fountain.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:14.000
In 1960, you were running the store?

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
Yes, he had died.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:25.000
I don't remember during that time, but at times we had problems of finding a black pharmacist

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:29.000
that wanted to come into a small town.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:35.000
And in the meantime, Craig's jokes still, the white track still filled that prescriptions for us.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:39.000
And was very helpful, in fact.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:46.000
What did you, what was your feeling about your role running that store and being in that position?

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:49.000
Did you enjoy that work? Did you?

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:53.000
Well, I used to have excursions that came from Baltimore.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:55.000
And hundreds of people would come.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:58.000
My grandfather would get, they would accept Craig.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
I was down by the war.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:07.000
And they would eat crabs and things, and they'd come uptown and go into the house home.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
And buy stuff.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:18.000
So I used to have to sell little things, cosmetics and things, and help out, you know, along the way.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:22.000
Both there, and then my grandfather's grocery store.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:28.000
But that was kind of because I was just really devastated about my father.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:34.000
And it was difficult getting people to come in and manage the jokes.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:41.000
My then husband, my father had been sending him to how pharmacy school was in F.D. Diody.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:44.000
That just kind of went all right.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.000
I don't think he was real interested.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:50.000
Tell me about W. You mentioned before we started today.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:57.000
But it was a good place to hear what everybody in the community thought was the freedom rights and the movement started.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:01.000
And I can carry information back and forth.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:08.000
And actually, the freedom rights and the SNCC field workers had been there almost a month before, in my uncle's house,

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:11.000
before I knew anything about it.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
Because I was working at the 12th clock and coming home.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:25.000
And to one day they came and said that my uncle said that I had a daughter and that a lot of people, her age gathered there on Saturdays to make cookies.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.000
And so I said, sure, you can go back and ask them.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
And that was the beginning of it.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:37.000
So I wanted some local guys to take them around the community, went on the weekends.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:41.000
And that was December, I think, late 61 by then.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:47.000
Late 61 running over into January.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:56.000
You mentioned that you sort of began in that first phase as an observer and students in younger folks, including your daughters.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:13.000
Oh, yes, they would have what they called the observer so that they would have somebody that if something went wrong, you know, that was seasoned enough, you know, to say what went on right or wrong and to, you know, the worn people.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:18.000
And then once or twice, I went on the, I went on the picket to mine.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
I finally decided to do that.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:32.000
And my daughter had to put me off the picket line because for whatever reason, as a grown woman, I thought I could, you know, walk some kind of way and trip these people that were spitting at you and stuff.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:33.000
That's going down.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
And she put me off because you were not.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
My mom get off.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:41.000
Because she didn't see you hearing perfectly.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:42.000
Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:43.000
No, she did.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:44.000
Yeah.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:47.000
So I thought, well, I don't think I'm cut out for this.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:56.000
So, yeah, tell me a little about how you were drawn into a leadership role.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:59.000
Oh, yes, they were.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:13.000
They had my, my cousin, Frederick Sanklair, who had been providing with his father, the bail, as the Freedom Riders went up and down the Eastern Shore,

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:21.000
said to one person, what you all really need to do in the place that really needs to be fixed is Cambridge, Maryland.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
So why don't you all stop off there?

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.000
So two of them did.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:31.000
And then they took, yeah, they had Bill Hansen, Reginald Robinson.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:38.000
So they didn't stay at my uncle's house and they started having Clawing and Community people.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:52.000
And who I wasn't part of that either, that supported the young people and whatnot.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:56.000
And then, Donna was involved.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:01.000
She claims this is, she didn't remember this, but I had my own daughter, Donna.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:11.000
She was one of the organizers, in turn, became one of the organizers of the high school students.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:22.000
And so, both high school and grammar school kids, when they practically stopped the town.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:30.000
And then the ministers went down and agreed that, well, if we have peace, we can't make a agree with White for.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:34.000
Unless you have peace, you can't negotiate.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:43.000
So one of the past, two of the past, three of these past, the parents that had gotten emotionally involved with the kids.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:53.000
And that's when they had a big mass meeting and decided to send people down to SNK and ask if we could have an adult group.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:20:04.000
And in that process, they asked me if I would take a leadership role there, because they felt at that time we weren't talking about violence.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:11.000
They thought that financially, I would not be jeopardized because there would be somebody that would take care of me, my family.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:16.000
And that's really, and my cousin and I went down to SNK agreed.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:35.000
And we came back and started going into laundry mats, the churches, the bars, and sending out little bad, they put together newsletters and organizing throughout the county.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:37.000
Let me ask you a little more about this topic.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:44.000
And then initially, we're going to pause for just a second.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:47.000
We'll look back. We'll back after a short break, please.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:50.000
Oh, okay. You were saying.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:52.000
Well, let me ask this if I could encourage that.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:55.000
Oh, our first thing was on voter registration. I didn't really believe in that.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:11.000
I just thought people had to be shown that because we've been voting still since 18th, one of the places on the show, that even though we voted and were hearing to all the things, still had segregated hospitals, housing, jobs to hold.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:17.000
But we thought that in general, people, that had to be brought to their attention.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:25.000
They may have realized that on some subterranean level, but in terms of, in their daily consciousness.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:35.000
And they gradually happened. Once we picked the people and won, and they thanked us very much for our support, but it's nothing we can do about the streets and stop whatever.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:38.000
Just mine or think, which you asked.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:44.000
I want to take you back to that spring 62, that trip to Atlanta to go down and meet the SNCC folks.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:45.000
Yes.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:50.000
You've written that you went down with, I think, white gloves and a very good skirt on.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:22:03.000
And you encountered the SNCC crew. And I'm interested in the transition from sort of that early experience to the, you would, you would very much build your own movement in Cambridge.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:04.000
Yes.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:07.000
I think it depends on the SNCC folks in many, when some leaders are in the...

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:13.000
Yeah, I don't think I'm real quite, I mean, looking back now, I can see that.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:23.000
We supported them, but we had moved away from the public accommodations. People would say to me, it was just true.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:30.000
Those are sleazy restaurants. I don't care what level, economic level, the person, oh, it's sleazy restaurant. What do we care about?

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:37.000
So, except for that you should have, you're right to go in there, should not be a bridge.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:51.000
But when we did the, when we, we, uh, uh, structured the survey, and what we called Junior CNAC, which were the grandma school kids, took it, took it throughout the community, it's done, brought it back.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:59.000
Volunteers from, from Swarthmore took it back to their professors and they did the, the right up in the correlation.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:07.000
From those facts of cards. And then it became clear that public accommodations were really at the bottom of the list.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:16.000
Housing, yes, with housing, jobs, you know, health issues. And we structured the demands around that.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:21.000
Describe that so you're, you're, you want the survey, which was very, um...

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:25.000
Thanks to you Franklin Frazier, I took a graduate course on to him.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:33.000
And I don't think he thought I had skills, but anyhow, at whatever level, you know, I learned, and we did that.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:45.000
And the questions on these cards were geared in those, you know, those main issues, executive board, and to see what people said about that and how they felt about it.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:52.000
Yeah, so you surveyed, you sent, I think, uh, the same children who were, high school students and others who were active in the community in the movement.

00:23:52.000 --> 00:24:03.000
That's true. To survey cards. To survey. And it really was the more the grammar school kids, because in the summer, the high school kids were out working to have the ticking of jobs.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:15.000
And your card, you had, so on the whole series of questions on the card, your priorities in the movement, your aspects about your, the condition of the house you live in, the, are you, all those things?

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:19.000
Yes, the, the, the plumbing, the, yeah.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:34.000
So you really did a, in a sense of basic solid systematic survey of conditions in, I know. And then after they, after they, they, they, uh, wrote it up and did the correlations, it swat more.

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:52.000
Actually, I think that's what, I think that's what changed Robert Kennedy's mind was it was perfectly clear that it was just a busily poor people that most of the component to their main being poor regeneration was racism.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:25:06.000
And I think he got involved more because out of his, Iris, and what they had done to the Irish when they came over that he was more sympathetic to the, to, to poverty.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:10.000
Tell me about that. I want to ask you.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:27.000
And so when we took that to him, and then that's when he started sending us around to, to his commission, commission, that, like, commission secretary of housing and, and, you know, various agencies that fit into that.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:30.000
I think by 62, especially 63.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:36.000
Yeah, just, just before and just after the agreement was signed.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:37.000
Yeah. Yeah.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:43.000
And of course weaver, we've been a friend of our mother said, we aren't, we, we're, we're doing the house.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:49.000
But as long as you all are in the streets, we are going to put a shovel in the ground.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:58.000
So that was, we didn't promise that we wouldn't be in the streets because we hit us two kids in the, in the West and sure.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:06.000
But, and of course passing the law to segregated housing.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:14.000
Let me ask about, I want to, I want to get all the more close to tale about this because it's just so interesting.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:25.000
One part of the reality of lives for many people in, in Black community, in Cambridge was housing was so poor that I think many people refer to it as, as, that the phrase was used chicken cups.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:27.000
No, they were actual chicken cups.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:28.000
Yeah, they have.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:33.000
Oh, I mean, that may, I may have totally blanked. They were chicken cups.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:43.000
Like, you know, and one on top of another and people were living in them.

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:50.000
And then, and I forget the names, their wife also collecting rent on it.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:54.000
And I think your survey showed unemployment in the Black community.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:55.000
Oh, 60%.

00:26:55.000 --> 00:27:01.000
Yes. Well, if someone was that today.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.000
Oh, you just aggregate the figures.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:04.000
Yes.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:08.000
It was high. But, but no. And that was even seasonal work.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:15.000
And, and, and because the city council except for one guy.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:19.000
And the aristocrats in town, you know,

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:23.000
had very low opinion of Black folks.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:30.000
And it was, it was Grahamville, hope, or who owned the whole fuel complex.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:34.000
That he eventually lost for being trying to be fair.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:41.000
And they tried to, they, they are the city ordered him not to send his fuel trucks out that one.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:49.000
And he said, if he had to get the Maryland State Police, he would send them out under guard.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:53.000
Because all the Black folks only worked part of their time in the year.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:58.000
They caught up with their bills with him when they worked.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:01.000
And of course, when we, when we had the urban renewal thing,

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:11.000
the first thing the city of fathers did was tear down his, you know, his, his business.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:14.000
Let me take you to the question I found.

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:22.000
How after the survey, your relationship would have, would evolve with, say, folks at SNCC and at the NAACP.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:25.000
And you knew what your community's goals were.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:27.000
You would build a local movement.

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:34.000
But oftentimes there were pressures from, especially from, say, NAACP leaders.

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:37.000
Oh, yeah. Well, we just ignored them after a while.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:42.000
By the, by the time they decided that they weren't going to sport this or that,

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:49.000
people in Cambridge, you know, had solidified and can, it didn't really matter.

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:53.000
Because they were, they, they were trying to push ahead and until the,

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:57.000
see, people's strength. In the beginning, you know, they were helpful.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:01.000
And I really think that's because in those first weeks, when SNCC came in,

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:08.000
they went around and, and urged people to join the NAACP and have the memberships.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:16.000
Then there was a period of time when, when people thought if you got in trouble with the law and when jail,

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:21.000
you could, because you were a member of the NAACP, you could ask one of their lawyers to come down and represent you.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:27.000
No, no, no, no. Because NAACP was to class contest in the first place.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:31.000
They didn't want to represent anybody unless, are they middle class?

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:39.000
Well, what did they mother or father do? So that was out.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:47.000
I think almost everyone, they brought me up here to a concert at Carnegie Hall.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:57.000
Because Martin was supposed to convince me on the referendum initiative to vote.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:06.000
So unfortunately, although I like Frank Sinatra and then you know, horn, I hate to leave because I was fast losing it.

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:14.000
And it's not that we didn't go out and support the Southern movement to get out of the vote.

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:21.000
But they tried a lot of stuff. I got letters from people with a few black folks that worked in the Maryland government.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:33.000
You know, wrong, please reconsider this, the daughter-daw offered the governor wanted to back me as a senator,

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:37.000
which I would say, which I was not interested in in first place.

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:40.000
And, and, and a variety of things.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:43.000
All these efforts have deflected you from your leadership role.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:47.000
Yes. And I think Miss Judd's became Bruce Movement.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:52.000
Right. Let's pause for just a sec.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:59.000
We're back on that, John. I think you want to be a mention that we're now recording without the cards.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:01.000
Correct. Okay.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:08.000
Mr. Anders, let me, you had mentioned the pattern of efforts to sort of deflect you from your leadership role in Cambridge.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:14.000
Because Cambridge had been so close to Washington DC, if it comes such a very, very active movement, a lot of national press coverage.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:17.000
So there were job offers. There was this.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.000
Oh, yeah. I forgot that. That's true. From the feds.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:23.000
The federal government offered you jobs, the state government offered you jobs.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:30.000
I offered it back before as a state senate candidate. They brought you to Carnegie Hall and had Frank Sinatra and Lena and other folks try to...

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:33.000
No, not them, but they had Martin.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:41.000
Yes. Martin, the guy from Johnson's guy from Texas Hobart Taylor.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:42.000
Yes.

00:31:42.000 --> 00:32:00.000
And that all puts me in mind of how rooted the movement was in Cambridge and how thoroughly well organized the community was in support of the movement in Cambridge.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:15.000
And I've read that you've written that there were probably 10 and 2014 core members who helped throughout the community that had come together as the heart of Sinatra.

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:24.000
That's right. It was probably on my grandfather's model, whoever the leader was in every neighborhood or who exactly, you know, people looked up to.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:26.000
Yeah. So you were the man or woman.

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:29.000
Right. And I wanted to ask about back point and the county.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:36.000
Right. So you found the people in all these different neighborhoods, cross-black community and county.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:46.000
I don't know whether found is a good word. I think I knew because came to just why I knew they were always there.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:33:06.000
I'm very interested in your experience at the head of the movement as a woman in relation to your fellow movement leaders in relation to communities that press.

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:19.000
Actually, I think in the first place, I was the only grandchild for a long time. Black folks had to use whatever they had.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:35.000
So within my family, there was no sense of you can't do this because your woman can't, you know, even the relationships with my grandmother and mother with the men in the family.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:42.000
After that, I think that was the basis of it.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:47.000
But even people in the SNCC tell me, and I think it's a silly of me.

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:53.000
But they say when they would mention things about, well, men aren't going to, the men aren't going to want us to do that.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:59.000
That I had no concept of how that would affect your behavior.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:04.000
Somebody just said that to me this year. And I can't even remember it.

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:11.000
I remember at some point, some lady called me from out in the Midwest and asked me, well, how are they doing that?

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:15.000
I can remember asking, what do you mean as a woman?

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:23.000
Because by that time, I think in Cambridge itself, there was, they may have been before, they may have been after.

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:31.000
They were not. Men went to work and came home and had to lay in the fields and around their houses, it could be fire bomb.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:38.000
The women were conducting the business down in the day because that they were available.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:46.000
So it was almost a divisional labor. Men went to work if something happened, the women could shoot, too.

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:58.000
So for that period of time, at least, I don't know what goes on now or what would be before, there was not that division.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:06.000
One night when the state police were marching up and down, and I had just begun to be involved.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:15.000
Women were on the street saying, if you all can beat us on Saturday night, don't you let these cops come through our community?

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:19.000
And they were slitting down. I thought, what?

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:28.000
And I think that whole thing grew. Now people like to say Cambridge was just the women's room, with that was not so.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:33.000
Yeah, no. I mean, it was a division of roles by necessity.

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:44.000
You mentioned the necessity of black men and others at times, women, even your daughter and mother at times guarding the black community.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:50.000
Oh, yeah, she did within the worst night. Yes, no.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:57.000
And Donna had to go through the, as we call the, the field part, the lead into people's yards.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:03.000
And because there was this secret, the men really organized themselves, secret whittles.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:10.000
If she had not known that or been like me and not been able to let's whistle, then she may very well have been shot.

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:14.000
She was trying to make it back to, because my mother was in the house alone.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:18.000
But they had, because it's a hunting country.

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:23.000
And so they both had been out hunting at one point or another.

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:28.000
And so she went up there and they got on the guns and went to see.

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:35.000
Let me ask about, and we were lucky because General Gilston was fair.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:40.000
And once he investigated, he courted Marcel, those guys, and then he'd come in.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:49.000
You referred to some national guardsmen who worked in, in, they were in a, in a different location.

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:52.000
Yes, and then I think we, and anyhow, yeah.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:59.000
Who had come through shooting up the black men at one night and they were fired black men and others in the community fired back.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:02.000
Oh, yeah, I was in the street that you did.

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:04.000
You could hear?

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:13.000
Yes, I understand. I wasn't on the pine street at that time, but they drove through shooting.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:26.000
Somebody had brought some machine gun home from the army from her war wanted to, to maybe.

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:32.000
In any of that, they were protecting that street, but they drove through the community.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:37.000
And when I was staying outside, I, I think I just recently read, but that is true.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:44.000
Even people that were not involved heavily involved in the movie, you could hear the clicks.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:50.000
Going down point, yes, wait, at every time they came through, they shot.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:54.000
The press was in my uncle's house under the tables.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:38:04.000
It was a bad night because in the morning at five or six o'clock, it was filled with, that smoke from Guns Ozone,

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:10.000
what the streets were just, fortunately nobody was, was hurt or killed.

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:21.000
The press was on pine street hanging out, but they had their cameras and stuff, and they caught the car coming through.

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:29.000
And so when Gielston asked, they told him if you subpoena us, we'll bring, you can have the pictures.

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:33.000
And he then caught my son, the people from.

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:36.000
This is the National Guard Commander in the movie.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:40.000
He said, black folks and capers loved him, yes.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:46.000
They think the government killed him because he didn't go to Walter Reed, something was wrong.

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:50.000
I think they think today, and I don't know.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:53.000
And then he did his job, and he was fair.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:59.000
He was going to arrest you and do whatever, but he wasn't malicious.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:07.000
You've had something over all these weeks and several months, you developed something in relationship with him across this movement activity.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:08.000
Yes.

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:17.000
And I, there's one irony, and you've touched on this and things you've written, that you were both aware separately that your phones were being tapped.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:25.000
Yes, he told me, when I went back there after the rep round incident, he told me yes.

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:37.000
And that that's why he used to send his number two guy back and forth to see that with whatever messages and negotiations or whatever we were doing because he didn't trust.

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:48.000
He said they would send it all the way down to Fort Bell, but Bell were, read it, send it back, and then send it as if it's coming through normally.

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:49.000
Yeah.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:56.000
Let me ask about your principal position in relation to the referendum on public accommodations.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:40:03.000
That was where so much of this pressure was brought to bear on you personally and on CNAC to support a referendum.

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:07.000
Can you talk about that whole experience and describe that situation?

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:12.000
Well, we didn't ever think we were supposed to vote on whether we could go into a restaurant.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:22.000
We were born here, blocks in Cambridge, you'd been there for 300 and so many years, a mixture of slave, free, freed.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:28.000
They had been restricted in certain communities, but they run businesses, run churches.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:33.000
In Cambridge, my grandfather's brother's set up school system.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:42.000
And I think there was some self-assurance you may not get in an strictly urban area where you're working for other people.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:47.000
And I forgot where I was going with this.

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:50.000
Oh, up to the right.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:41:01.000
So as I said earlier, people thought most of them were greasy spoons because occasionally they did get to the city and go to a decent restaurant.

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:08.000
And men had just come back from fighting.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:16.000
So I thought it was a normal position and so did everybody else.

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:31.000
Except the NAACP court, the Baltimore Ministers, is this everybody outside of Cambridge.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:42.000
And I don't know whether it was because they were pressured and thought against the deep south that it made more sense.

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:50.000
But we never were pushing that.

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:56.000
I just saw in the crisis, I didn't know it was on the internet.

00:41:56.000 --> 00:42:06.000
The article in the crisis magazine about it and their field secretary, even at the agreement, was talking as if the public accommodations was the big thing.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:10.000
And I guess it was for them.

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:12.000
But your position?

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:19.000
But then yeah, because if you're born here and then here, and you know what?

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:26.000
The Kennedy's invited Robert Kennedy and invited you to White House.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:36.000
Yes. I think that was because I think we were having a conference with the governor in Baltimore,

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:48.000
but something happened when we out of town and about 200 blacks and 200, 300 whites almost came together on Ray Street.

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:51.000
And everybody got scared.

00:42:51.000 --> 00:43:00.000
The guy standing in branch and Phil Savage, branch who, I don't know what about Savage,

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:06.000
the branch turned out to be FBI for them.

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:10.000
When I got back, they were all upset and died and died.

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:13.000
Oh, it's going to be a civil war and died and died.

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:18.000
And I thought, was it really that bad?

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:26.000
But anyhow, whatever happened, I don't know whether the press called Robert Kennedy.

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:34.000
They claimed that Robert Kennedy called there, but that started the whole meeting.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:45.000
Now, they had been in a relationship between seeing that, and the White House through Galston,

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:54.000
and the whole Maria's father's, Sargent's father were friends.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:44:03.000
And then the friend of my family that had been in civil rights division, the Maceo Hubbard,

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:06.000
but it had not gotten to that point.

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:13.000
And so they told us we had to come up there.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:22.000
And of course, it may have been, because Galston tells me that there's stuff going on that we knew about our hair would have been white then.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:31.000
But anyhow, I remember distinctly, and I thought, gee, was almost every cross-thera-fare from Cambridge to Washington,

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:36.000
there were police cars stationed and they turned us off.

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:48.000
So I thought gee, but then subsequent, subsequent conversations, they said that, you know, it was just simply too dangerous.

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:56.000
In fact, on that meeting, they had a woman at the White House that my uncle took me to what we thought was backfire.

00:44:56.000 --> 00:45:00.000
Apparently, was a shot over a fighter.

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:04.000
And we kept on going because we said, gee, it's backfire.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:11.000
But when I got back that night, because we went to visit some people in Washington, and I guess disappeared from some radar,

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:16.000
when I got back, the press was in my living room, and the word had gone out, we'd been killed.

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:18.000
Is that right?

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:20.000
Yeah.

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:23.000
And I had, you know, reflecting back now, I think, what?

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:27.000
But at that time, my old reaction was, that's crazy.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:29.000
What do you want?

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:31.000
This was this going from all in Cambridge?

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:34.000
Cambridge, Washington and back, yes.

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:41.000
What were your strategies, mechanisms for dealing with all that pressure and fear?

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:47.000
I don't know. I think, I mean, I'm not saying that I was never afraid.

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:56.000
I don't know. I always depended that I always thought, well, if they get me, those people in Cambridge will get them.

00:45:56.000 --> 00:46:02.000
And then I used to recite this thing from Quillenwood Cray, you know, if I'm pinned to, I'm paraphrased that.

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:09.000
If I'm pinned against the wall like a hole, let me not die like one.

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:20.000
And although I'm secular and the part of the wall walk through the shadow, I used to repeat that.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:24.000
You went to jail for a couple of weeks in the spring of 1963.

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:25.000
Yeah.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:28.000
And...

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:33.000
First of all, somebody arrested me in the army. I had to go over in the barracks instead.

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:36.000
Yeah. And did you get the army?

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:42.000
Well, the week, yes. Because I think Donna and my mother both were there.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:56.000
And what happened was my mother could not believe that some little corner, Coca-Cola place, was not going to serve her.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:03.000
They'd grown up in Cambridge. They'd come in some little sheep's store.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:12.000
And so she was going to go to show that it could be done and got arrested.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:20.000
Donna and the young people also got arrested. But they...

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:27.000
It was right after whatever happened and suddenly, and they were in jeans and stuff. They went in their school clothes.

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:39.000
So when they got in jail, they decided among themselves that they would go out, go home, put on jeans, and go lay in the theaters there.

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:45.000
Did not tell us. I thought, oh, there's no one with these children. Are they turning into Uncle Tom's?

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:55.000
And of course, by that time, the jail process, people were asking, you have kids 13 and 14, and what are you doing?

00:47:55.000 --> 00:48:10.000
And so they were anxious to get them out and keep us. And they did that. When they laid in the theaters after they changed their clothes, the police went back and picked them up and beat them.

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:18.000
And the adult advisors on the street saw it and went back, house knocking on doors. They're killing our kids.

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:25.000
And then the whole town poured out. I think about 12 o'clock, and we kept thinking, what is this roar? It's this big roar.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:34.000
And we got on our toes and peaked out to do the jail cells. And I said, I think there's people. And it was.

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:44.000
In the nightgowns and everything, just pouring this was way, way, way we should always say, don't go too far from the second world because we can't get out there, you know, and help you.

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:56.000
So don't, like that whole thing with Army, don't get too far ahead of your supply line. That's why I thought they were going to mess up and they're wrong, but anyhow.

00:48:56.000 --> 00:49:08.000
And then they filled the tails. And then when Cambridge started asking Surrounder and Towns to take them, they wouldn't do it. No, we ain't going to have that mess over here.

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:22.000
And they eventually had to free some people in order to make space for other people. But that's, you know, that's when I think the entire town came together.

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:30.000
Yeah. Your trial would result in a one cent fine. When you tell that story?

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:47.000
Yes, the judge was laryd handy. And we went through the trial and testified. I was really surprised. I didn't know what he was going to do. But I think he was conflicted.

00:49:47.000 --> 00:50:05.000
I'm not sure why. I know what the rumor is. But I think he formed a committee and we refused to come out of jail to be so thinking. But he did form a committee, you know, based on our demands.

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:26.000
So the rumor was afterwards that he, he for a while had to go in a rest. Tell him, I don't know whether that's true or not. But I think he was conflicted because that, that dissuessing charges of the penny fine was, and he did it very seriously. You know, we were like, what? What does this mean?

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:42.000
And of course, he gave me a five minute lecture on my position, my grandfather. What was I thinking about? What did I have to demonstrate about?

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:49.000
I wasn't Cambridge fine. And so on.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:59.000
Can you recall the night when the citizens council brought George Wallace to town?

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:16.000
Yes, almost everybody up and down because black, white, priest, whatever came into Cambridge. Some of the snake people didn't want to march. But Wallace had been all over the state of Maryland.

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:37.000
And with some people in Cambridge backing him. The, I'm not sure that all of the articles about the fire department, but not only was it segregated, but they had been out in the black community and black folks that contributed to a $3,000 building thing.

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:47.000
And then they were told they couldn't come in. So that was a big and that Wallace would come and choose that place to do the speech.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:55.000
It was like, you know, ten of us. And then they used that bag, what was it, CN2 or something? No, that's CN2 gas.

00:51:55.000 --> 00:52:09.000
Yes, they used that gas. And the baby they talked about, the local doctor went and they didn't autopsy and boil them more.

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:19.000
I don't know whether it was actually true that the gas did not do it or whether because of the situation.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:37.000
And we kept questioning that, but that's all we got. It was not, you know, two-junk gas. But that was, and I think, Gilston joked afterwards that the wind changed and the gas blew over on the other side of town.

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:44.000
And on the soldiers, but they had sent the autos as brother in there. Who's brother?

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:58.000
General Tos is brother. He was not in leadership because when they put us in the army trucks and I said to them, oh, you know, we want to talk to General Gilston.

00:52:58.000 --> 00:53:05.000
And it's just a perfectly cold flight. Three or four times I thought, what the hell is wrong with them?

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:15.000
But I did not know that it was only the Tos guy there. And I think he was among other things besides being mean, just scared you death.

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:26.000
And that use of CN2 gas was reported the time to have been the first ever instance of the civilian use of that gas?

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:36.000
It may be the only time because except when Hillary Clinton made the mistake of apologizing to, oh, what's the guy's name? Oh, by them using it over there.

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:40.000
In Palestine, here.

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:52.000
But that night you were earlier looting to the fact that one elderly man and an infant died and it was believed that their contingents had been so seriously taken by the gas.

00:53:52.000 --> 00:54:01.000
And they said people were crawling on the ground. They had taken some of us out. But it made us sick because the people they arrested with us had it in their clothes.

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:09.000
And when they took us over to Baltimore County, you know, you could smell it.

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:17.000
And then of course they didn't know what to do because they didn't know how to try us.

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:22.000
So there was all that after all this stuff went on.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:24.000
Sure. Yeah.

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:31.000
Let's spend a few minutes talking about the March on Washington, which would be a very interesting day in so many respects.

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:32.000
Okay.

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:41.000
Let's take a quick look at personally the only one.

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:43.000
Okay. We're back after a short break.

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:46.000
I want to ask about March on Washington.

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:49.000
Okay.

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:55.000
I understand that a few weeks before the event, you were asked to come and participate.

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:58.000
And then some very interesting.

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:04.000
I don't think that was of the free will. I think somebody must have said, how can you do this?

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:09.000
I don't know who, but for a long time, let's add some more women to the program.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:12.000
Probably.

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:18.000
And then on the day of the March on Washington, you had to think very carefully about what you would wear.

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:23.000
Oh, yes, because they call me and tell me not to wear jeans.

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:28.000
So then I went all across Eastern Shore and Pearl and looked what we weren't shopping in Cambridge.

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:31.000
We've shopped in Seoul for it by then.

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:35.000
Looking for something in denim, which isn't like today.

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:42.000
That was a skirt or a dress, but still would be, we call them dunger-reased.

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:44.000
Still be that material.

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:51.000
And finally, in one store found this skirt with the straps.

00:55:51.000 --> 00:56:00.000
Then when I got there, also Snicken made us coordinators for organizing people of the Eastern Shore.

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:04.000
But I mean, Malcolm's right.

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:07.000
It seemed to me it was turning into a big party.

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:18.000
When a lot of us were out in the streets, you know, very threatened when you're going to have all this music and a picnic.

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:25.000
But any event, everybody seems to want to do it and doubt it, so we, in some people, came originally.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:33.000
We only supplied the buses and packing house, you know, not one in Cambridge.

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:35.000
And so we went.

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:42.000
When I got to the March tent, there were these women there.

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:49.000
They had loads of parts, whatever, briefly talked.

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:54.000
And I said, then, when I got up and said, well, we're coming to the ladies room.

00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:56.000
Oh, okay.

00:56:56.000 --> 00:56:58.000
So I said then, waiting for them to come back.

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:04.000
And the meantime, somebody from Europe somewhere was doing a satellite thing.

00:57:04.000 --> 00:57:06.000
I went and did that and came back.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:09.000
I thought, gee, this is a long time.

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:12.000
And Bayer rust and popped up.

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:14.000
And he said, what are you doing here?

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:16.000
So I said, what do you mean, what are you doing here?

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:18.000
Well, I'm in your toilet.

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:23.000
No, he said, out there, it had marched.

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:28.000
I thought, oh!

00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:35.000
So he took me through the crowds and took me to the stage.

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:41.000
And when we got there, it was either...

00:57:41.000 --> 00:57:43.000
The two of them were sitting together.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:47.000
I think it was...

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:49.000
You got Lena Horn?

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:55.000
It was Lena Horn, but I can't believe this.

00:57:55.000 --> 00:58:02.000
The European dancer, and she went and despised the war.

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:05.000
She couldn't work over here.

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:06.000
We'll get it.

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:07.000
Yes.

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:10.000
I'll make it a problem to come back and see her now.

00:58:10.000 --> 00:58:13.000
They said to me, as soon as they brought me to...

00:58:13.000 --> 00:58:14.000
She said, they...

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:17.000
They removed your chair.

00:58:17.000 --> 00:58:20.000
You need to go and customise about that.

00:58:20.000 --> 00:58:24.000
So when I looked over chairs were filled.

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:26.000
And I said, what do you mean?

00:58:26.000 --> 00:58:27.000
They took your chair.

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:29.000
Then I knew the whole thing was planned.

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:33.000
Not accident, or, you know, this just happened.

00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:35.000
So I said, well, forget about it.

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:37.000
And I saw Robert Ming from Chicago,

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:40.000
and it was some legal thing that we had going on in Cambridge.

00:58:40.000 --> 00:58:42.000
And I wanted to talk to him about...

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:45.000
I said, no, let me go into the back of these people here,

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:47.000
because I want to talk to this guy.

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:49.000
And that's what I did.

00:58:49.000 --> 00:58:54.000
So then when they called me, I came from the back.

00:58:54.000 --> 00:58:57.000
And I was going to tell people to sit there until they passed the Lord.

00:58:57.000 --> 00:58:59.000
Don't leave town.

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:05.000
And as I said, hello, an NAACP guy.

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:08.000
That's nice to me.

00:59:08.000 --> 00:59:11.000
Then they took me and Lena Horn,

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:14.000
because she had gotten roads of parks,

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:19.000
and was presenting her to the International Satellite and things.

00:59:19.000 --> 00:59:20.000
Media.

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:21.000
Media.

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:25.000
And when I found that out, I went to help her,

00:59:25.000 --> 00:59:27.000
because they would have been no Martin.

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:30.000
They've never had been roads of parks.

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:33.000
So I think they were annoyed at both of us.

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:37.000
And before Martin spoke, they put us in a taxi and sent us back to the hotel.

00:59:37.000 --> 00:59:39.000
What was the rationale they gave for that?

00:59:39.000 --> 00:59:41.000
They didn't want us to be crushed.

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:42.000
But they were crowds.

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:43.000
Yes.

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:44.000
Getting out.

00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:47.000
Well, everybody else on the platform was okay.

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:52.000
How about your...

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:55.000
And then in the meantime, my daughter was out there being interviewed.

00:59:55.000 --> 01:00:00.000
And she said, well, I don't understand this. It's a picnic.

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:06.000
So that was the position that people from Cambridge did.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:11.000
Can you reflect a little bit about John Kennedy, Robert Kennedy?

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:13.000
You touched on that a little bit earlier.

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:16.000
But ultimately, how you're abused those two men and the...

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:20.000
I like Robert Kennedy.

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:22.000
I think there are probably three people.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:26.000
I don't like to watch them on TV today, or it's difficult.

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:30.000
That's Adam, Robert Kennedy, Malcolm.

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:32.000
When you say Adam, you mean...

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:33.000
Powell.

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:35.000
Yes, okay.

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:42.000
Adam got that food into Cambridge at a lot of stuff.

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:44.000
And put it in the Cambridge.

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:45.000
Adam got that food into Cambridge.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:46.000
Can you describe them?

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:47.000
Well, yes.

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:53.000
We had applied for the in-ghost and admitted that they needed food.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:00:57.000
It was surplus food before it went into food stamps.

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:01.000
And Adam had arranged for that to go on.

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:06.000
The City Council in Cambridge and the governor said, no, nobody was starving.

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:07.000
Nobody needed food.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:10.000
And he fought that fight.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:20.000
And in fact, Cambridge was so whatever that the guard had to offer to distribute the food.

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:31.000
And then, white folks in the other side of town started calling us saying they had been threatened to be thrown off a welfare if they showed up at any of those sites where they were distributing it.

01:01:31.000 --> 01:01:35.000
So the black men, you know, they...

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:38.000
Because they worked with them and stuff.

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:40.000
And they knew who needed food.

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:43.000
So they loaded up their vans and stuff and took it out to them.

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:44.000
To the white people?

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:45.000
Yeah.

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:48.000
That's in the middle of all this other stuff.

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:49.000
So you mentioned it.

01:01:49.000 --> 01:01:52.000
Also, the union was trying to organize.

01:01:52.000 --> 01:02:03.000
And in the middle of all the fight, blacks and whites met at a black rod and gun club to process the union here from...

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:05.000
I mean, it was here in New York.

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:11.000
The stuff they made in Cambridge went all over the country and were on that.

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:12.000
I can't think of the name.

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:13.000
You know, Parallel, isn't it?

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:14.000
Huh?

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:15.000
I don't work with someone.

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:21.000
Yeah, it's garment workers union, but I can't think of the robberweight, you're right.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:23.000
That was in Parallel Company.

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:25.000
And they were paying lower wages for the same working.

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:27.000
Yes, to everybody.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:34.000
So the issue was not jobs, but we all that work in this industry more better wages.

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:36.000
That was something of its sense.

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:41.000
The ironic, isn't it, that at the same time all of these tensions had divided Cambridge.

01:02:41.000 --> 01:02:42.000
Yes.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:47.000
That in the very near term you have black and white union groups working together.

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:49.000
Not near term, right in the middle of it.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:56.000
Yeah, and trying to build some interracial union effort to achieve better side.

01:02:56.000 --> 01:03:02.000
And they blocked them from meeting in any...

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:05.000
In their American, whatever their facilities were.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:07.000
They would not let them meet.

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:08.000
You know what I mean?

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:14.000
The board on the broadened gun company, they can meet here if they're okay with it.

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:22.000
And yes, and I went to one meeting with some of the CNAC people.

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:27.000
And they, as luck they tell me happened in Appalachia when Snick went there,

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:36.000
they actually asked the black guys to voice their complaints to these people from New York.

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:44.000
Because they were afraid, I guess, of the people that control Cambridge.

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:46.000
Oh, I see, the white men.

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:47.000
Yes, the black guys.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:48.000
Yeah, yeah.

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:50.000
Yeah, no, they didn't know.

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:53.000
And they asked some of the black guys to go.

01:03:53.000 --> 01:03:55.000
Sure, yeah.

01:03:55.000 --> 01:03:57.000
But they say that happened in Appalachia.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:01.000
Some Snick people went there and they said, we will have to speak.

01:04:01.000 --> 01:04:05.000
Not because they couldn't speak, but because...

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:10.000
Following through all this history, we haven't yet talked about Malcolm X.

01:04:10.000 --> 01:04:20.000
And I know that that's an important part of this story and your sense of this history in Poland.

01:04:20.000 --> 01:04:31.000
I had heard about Malcolm from people who left Cambridge and went into Army and were living in Philadelphia, Baltimore.

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:34.000
I had not heard him myself.

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:44.000
And I went and I didn't think very highly of Elijah, Muhammad, and whatever that was.

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:49.000
But anyhow, I went to Chicago.

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:52.000
Reverend Franklin was having this big thing with SCLC.

01:04:52.000 --> 01:04:56.000
SCLC was trying to move into the cities.

01:04:56.000 --> 01:04:58.000
And when I got there...

01:04:58.000 --> 01:04:59.000
Detroit.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:05.000
When I got there, several people said to me, you are in the wrong place.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:12.000
And I said, well, they said, you know, Malcolm is going to be over at Albert Cleans Church, Reverend Cleans Church.

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:14.000
That's where you should be.

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:17.000
And I said, well, who is Reverend Cleans?

01:05:17.000 --> 01:05:18.000
And I explained.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:20.000
So I said, well, I really would like...

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:23.000
Yeah, no, I thought to myself, I'd like to hear him speak.

01:05:23.000 --> 01:05:30.000
So I went over there and then they asked me up on the stage and then he spoke.

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:35.000
I thought, oh, I thought then he was going to leave...

01:05:35.000 --> 01:05:37.000
Nation of Islam.

01:05:37.000 --> 01:05:38.000
Nation of Islam.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:45.000
There was something, all he said, the honorable Elijah, Muhammad, the da da da, but it was something in the tone that I thought,

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:49.000
I don't think he's going to be there very long.

01:05:49.000 --> 01:05:58.000
But in any event, the guy from Cambridge, Bob Pannett, who had a clinic there, he almost turned his head totally around.

01:05:58.000 --> 01:06:00.000
He couldn't get over it.

01:06:00.000 --> 01:06:06.000
And so that was my first, you know, personal meeting with Malcolm.

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:08.000
I'm sorry, Mr. Bennett, couldn't get over what exactly?

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:11.000
He couldn't get over Malcolm X. He just turned his head around.

01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:18.000
This is a wealthy, upper middle class black and Detroit who has a medical clinic and daughter, daughter, came from Cambridge.

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:21.000
You know, just told full success.

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:28.000
And I don't think he was airing or anything like that, but he just never heard this before.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:31.000
And he said, my God, I've never...

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:41.000
I think he talked over the next day and then he invited some of the SC, not, not, not some of the SCO, see people over to dinner.

01:06:41.000 --> 01:06:44.000
And then after that, I don't remember too clearly.

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:50.000
I think we invited him to Cambridge when he was going to Africa.

01:06:50.000 --> 01:07:00.000
And then at Act, because the men, we invited him there and he came.

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:08.000
I'm not really sure because he was doing the ballot and bullets thing.

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:21.000
And I thought that before the election, he should make a clear of Go boarder was running that it should not be ballots and he agreed.

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:23.000
The decision not be ballots, right?

01:07:23.000 --> 01:07:25.000
Yes.

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:32.000
So, you know, we went through the, the, the act thing.

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:44.000
And then, actually, the night he was killed, I had been up to one of his things at the, um, Audubon.

01:07:44.000 --> 01:07:48.000
But I was also supposed to be there the day that he was killed.

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:52.000
Can I hear it in the air? I couldn't believe that.

01:07:52.000 --> 01:07:53.000
Is that right?

01:07:53.000 --> 01:07:54.000
Yeah.

01:07:54.000 --> 01:08:04.000
And the fact that actually we had been, my mother had agreed once that first bomb and the house happened.

01:08:04.000 --> 01:08:17.000
She had a, in the parsnage in New Jersey, she had a almost totally complete third floor that his family could go over there and stay.

01:08:17.000 --> 01:08:19.000
So you were going to, huh?

01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:21.000
Your mother offered housing to.

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:35.000
And so we were going through arranging that and did he really need it because also before I left Cambridge, the, the, um,

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:41.000
I have a picture with the, uh, my Hamid speaks for Targolford from Baltimore.

01:08:41.000 --> 01:08:49.000
He came to me and told me the Honourful Elijah, my Hamid, told me to tell you, you need to stay off of the stage with Malcolm X.

01:08:49.000 --> 01:08:55.000
So I told him, you are a well-known Elijah, my Hamid has nothing to do with me.

01:08:55.000 --> 01:08:57.000
But I think that was a warning.

01:08:57.000 --> 01:09:05.000
It was after he was trying to, was the nation is, I'm trying to wiggle out of that chicken coming home to roost off.

01:09:05.000 --> 01:09:13.000
But now this was like, what, six or seven months later, my time frames are sometimes off.

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:19.000
So no, we were trying so, so then, you know, that was like a shock.

01:09:19.000 --> 01:09:25.000
I don't know what Maribol said about that because I can't get past, past 62.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:27.000
You're referring to the Man of Maribol?

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:28.000
Yes.

01:09:28.000 --> 01:09:39.000
I have something in there he sounds, I've heard him before my union had him but I think he's kind of patronizing.

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:43.000
I thought he was patronizing there talking about the civil rights.

01:09:43.000 --> 01:09:47.000
We were all though he may have had his story, historical facts, right?

01:09:47.000 --> 01:09:55.000
And I think he, I've sensed that in the book and I have my son in law, but I haven't been able to get past 62.

01:09:55.000 --> 01:09:59.000
And now they tell me this someplace in the book, I don't know whether it's true or not,

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:03.000
where he says his biggest mistake was appearing on the stage with me.

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:11.000
Some review said that, but I think the, I just, I doubt very seriously if he's caught Malcolm.

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:15.000
The very fact that he says he reinvent himself.

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:21.000
I think reinvent is a poor, sure, a swirled, I think he grew.

01:10:21.000 --> 01:10:30.000
I have to ask, so, so someone at the time observed of Malcolm X that his most significant mistake was appearing on the stage with you?

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:46.000
Yes, one of these reviews. I think I just, I think I just sent it to, to, I'm going to look in the book, so I have to book this, the page.

01:10:46.000 --> 01:10:54.000
But the, can you, can you say a little bit more about that would have been a mistake because you were...

01:10:54.000 --> 01:10:59.000
Oh, I guess I was worth, I was a bad figure for him to be on the stage.

01:10:59.000 --> 01:11:06.000
Because you had become, you had become identified, how would you sum up how, how you had become known and recognized?

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:15.000
What did people understand you to represent by that time?

01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:21.000
At the time, I don't know. I was just glad the press was there because they picked up the issues.

01:11:21.000 --> 01:11:26.000
They learned while they came in, they didn't know what the hell was going on beginning.

01:11:26.000 --> 01:11:30.000
And of course they were meeting with the ministries and the town fathers and stuff.

01:11:30.000 --> 01:11:35.000
But the longer they stayed, they began to, that was true of the guard.

01:11:35.000 --> 01:11:46.000
We thought the guard was there to keep us in. Why folks thought the guard was there to, I mean, we thought the, they thought the guard was there to protect us.

01:11:46.000 --> 01:11:53.000
And we thought the guard was there to keep us in. And then they started fighting the guard and spitting on them and throwing things on.

01:11:53.000 --> 01:11:57.000
Which made the guard, as Gelson said, probably didn't care one way or the other.

01:11:57.000 --> 01:12:04.000
But they fell on the little ladies, the ladies in our community when they standing guard on the corner in the hot summer time,

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:14.000
would go out and carry on lemonade and stuff. You know, so these guys kind of got, oh, you know, these would be intriguing nicely.

01:12:14.000 --> 01:12:18.000
Let's take a little break and then we'll come back.

01:12:19.000 --> 01:12:20.000
Okay.

01:12:20.000 --> 01:12:23.000
Ms. Tantra, let's do a final five or ten minutes.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:24.000
Okay.

01:12:24.000 --> 01:12:26.000
Let's wrap up a little bit.

01:12:26.000 --> 01:12:38.000
You had emerged as a figure recognized nationally, I think, across the movement as someone who really had, through her efforts and her position in the community,

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:44.000
through the strength of your local movement, had really emerged as a uniquely independent, independent movement leader.

01:12:44.000 --> 01:13:02.000
And I'm interested in your thoughts about that and how you thought about managing your relationship with not only the folks you work with in Cambridge,

01:13:02.000 --> 01:13:10.000
but all these national figures who reached or interacted with you in these different ways, oftentimes, with a lot of tension.

01:13:10.000 --> 01:13:34.000
I think that's probably a good question, but I had been raised, I think, from my family, both parents and grandparents, to look at people and judge them not by titles,

01:13:34.000 --> 01:13:42.000
or whatever surrounded them with that title, and for good or bad judge them.

01:13:42.000 --> 01:13:57.000
So, I really did not have a kind of awe of what are normally important people.

01:13:57.000 --> 01:14:18.000
And also, I think my independence came from the people I was representing, and their determination, because I always knew they were there,

01:14:18.000 --> 01:14:29.000
and maintaining kind of a creative chaos for months.

01:14:29.000 --> 01:14:40.000
And in balance there, that in the end, we should be able to achieve something, or else nothing is worthwhile.

01:14:40.000 --> 01:14:54.000
And I think that's what happened. The guard had to come in and out from each county and rotate. They didn't always have jobs when they went back, the state was spending more and more money.

01:14:54.000 --> 01:15:03.000
The Kennedys were representing themselves as life savers to Africa and emerging countries.

01:15:03.000 --> 01:15:12.000
And here you have within an hour and a half or two hours, what is this, and what are you doing about it?

01:15:12.000 --> 01:15:31.000
And I think a combination of that, and maybe, I think I didn't think that hadn't, but maybe now, because I was a woman, but they were, you know, there are other women in SNCC that,

01:15:31.000 --> 01:15:43.000
and also, I have to say, with SNCC they let local people decide what, and who, and they did not interfere with it.

01:15:43.000 --> 01:15:54.000
I think Foreman was a little upset when he asked me about Malcolm, but actually he couldn't order me to not have anything to do with Malcolm X.

01:15:54.000 --> 01:16:04.000
Oh, yes, but the thing, do you think, you know, he's very, he's not nonviolent, he's very, yes, no, he called me.

01:16:04.000 --> 01:16:12.000
And I said, okay, fine, you all have to be connected to him, just let us, you know, we'll do it.

01:16:12.000 --> 01:16:26.000
But he didn't push it, he just, you know, that one phone call, that's why I was always amused at after SNCC met Malcolm, and they, you know, as when they had tried all this other stuff and moving it in another direction.

01:16:26.000 --> 01:16:47.000
I sat in, I think it was Bird Marshall's office before his office, one day, while they waited to see what Roy, everybody, Roy Wilkins was going to say in doubt it died.

01:16:47.000 --> 01:16:55.000
And then in the end, I, you know, I had to tell them they have nothing to do with this. They don't have the people in the street.

01:16:55.000 --> 01:17:14.000
So for better or worse, you're going to have to deal here. And we're not members of the organization, and actually, even core who was known to be active, except for Brooklyn core, was not too happy with it.

01:17:17.000 --> 01:17:25.000
I basically, I heard, call G once and tried to talk you into changing your position.

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:38.000
This is a guy that used to, what he used to visit on a weekend parties and cabries was sending me and my cousins out and give us a penny if we went to this store and bought three cigarettes out of the package.

01:17:39.000 --> 01:17:53.000
No, he came down there and they, you know, they offered a job and did the job strength. What did they call it then for the Eastern Shore Merlin?

01:17:54.000 --> 01:18:02.000
And talked to my mother, they were friends, and they were friends of his wife.

01:18:02.000 --> 01:18:12.000
But, you know, that was not relevant. He may have been surprised, but Roy Wiley sat in my house almost a riot of rock-to-cold.

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:18.000
He ran out of coal for the car and coal for this, and coal for Washington.

01:18:18.000 --> 01:18:29.000
But I think he had come in and out of Cambridge as a young man going to school with my uncles and cousins and had a relationship with his family.

01:18:29.000 --> 01:18:37.000
I think they thought that that might have, and my mother, I think, was here following forward, but anyhow.

01:18:37.000 --> 01:18:46.000
Because I had these children, I was getting to fours, you know, what, and she was going to have to support me.

01:18:46.000 --> 01:18:49.000
But I said no.

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:57.000
I'm trying, gently, to lead you up to that point because you had a choice message one time that you conveyed to President Kennedy and I was worth remembering.

01:18:57.000 --> 01:19:00.000
Through Macy, I hope it yes.

01:19:00.000 --> 01:19:07.000
Whatever it was, I told him to Kennedy brothers, we'd go to hell, but now I don't remember what he was they wanted.

01:19:07.000 --> 01:19:08.000
I think they did.

01:19:08.000 --> 01:19:12.000
If I said before, that's probably what it is, but I can't.

01:19:12.000 --> 01:19:16.000
I remember where I was sitting in my uncles. I was sitting on a step with the telephone.

01:19:16.000 --> 01:19:20.000
If it's something we were either getting ready to do or...

01:19:20.000 --> 01:19:23.000
Did you want to put a little Cambridge?

01:19:23.000 --> 01:19:27.000
Yeah, oh yeah, no.

01:19:27.000 --> 01:19:35.000
And it probably would have been, I think it probably would have been more people shot and killed if that...

01:19:35.000 --> 01:19:43.000
Why can't I remember his first name? If the tall is guy, he was really Gelsen's boss.

01:19:43.000 --> 01:19:46.000
Gelsen was at the teacher.

01:19:46.000 --> 01:19:48.000
And he was there.

01:19:48.000 --> 01:19:56.000
If he had been there over the guard, but through all that time, I think things may have been messier.

01:19:57.000 --> 01:20:01.000
On balance, Gelsen managed to keep that.

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:04.000
Yes, I think...

01:20:04.000 --> 01:20:15.000
I remember when I first saw him, I was with Savage and Branch at the City Council having a meeting.

01:20:15.000 --> 01:20:17.000
He just walked in and sat down.

01:20:17.000 --> 01:20:22.000
Go Savage and Branch jumped up and down. Who is this man? He has no business being here.

01:20:23.000 --> 01:20:28.000
Instead of Gelsen getting upset or insulted, he just said, fine, I'll leave.

01:20:28.000 --> 01:20:37.000
And I thought, oh, he must have a lot of power with somebody because he didn't do the ordinary thing.

01:20:37.000 --> 01:20:41.000
What do you mean, I'm staying? And it proved that he did.

01:20:41.000 --> 01:20:44.000
You mentioned earlier in the interview that...

01:20:44.000 --> 01:20:46.000
I think you mentioned, was it Branch or Savage?

01:20:46.000 --> 01:20:48.000
Was later a determinant of an FBI informant?

01:20:48.000 --> 01:20:50.000
Branch.

01:20:51.000 --> 01:20:55.000
That parent, Miss Perry Mitchell's papers must have that.

01:20:55.000 --> 01:20:56.000
He...

01:20:56.000 --> 01:21:06.000
Well, Branch, when the Swarthmore kids came into Cambridge with the kids from the other college,

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:12.000
and planted some kind of civil rights organization, and they had been from Swarthmore, Baton,

01:21:13.000 --> 01:21:15.000
and then...

01:21:15.000 --> 01:21:22.000
Oh, that was really stupid because I think he had been a detective in a store.

01:21:22.000 --> 01:21:29.000
But anyhow, he started coming in and out of Cambridge, and he was connected also with the NCAP.

01:21:29.000 --> 01:21:34.000
But he was really in and out of everything.

01:21:34.000 --> 01:21:35.000
And when they...

01:21:35.000 --> 01:21:38.000
Actually, the people that told me about it were those...

01:21:38.000 --> 01:21:40.000
With the anti-war...

01:21:40.000 --> 01:21:43.000
Oh, now I can't think of their names.

01:21:43.000 --> 01:21:50.000
They broke into the media-pensive thing, FBI, Office,

01:21:50.000 --> 01:21:55.000
Priests, and nuns, the brothers.

01:21:55.000 --> 01:21:57.000
I can't think of their names.

01:21:57.000 --> 01:21:58.000
That's okay.

01:21:58.000 --> 01:22:00.000
And they write at the moment.

01:22:00.000 --> 01:22:05.000
And then they sent me word that in the papers that they got,

01:22:05.000 --> 01:22:09.000
that he had been reporting back and forth through that.

01:22:09.000 --> 01:22:10.000
How did you...

01:22:10.000 --> 01:22:16.000
Because he almost shot Stokely one night, who came through there, unannounced.

01:22:16.000 --> 01:22:17.000
And we were...

01:22:17.000 --> 01:22:21.000
And when I went downstairs, I found him there, you know, with the gun.

01:22:21.000 --> 01:22:26.000
But we just thought that was accident because, you know, there were guns all over the house,

01:22:26.000 --> 01:22:28.000
and case somebody came in.

01:22:28.000 --> 01:22:30.000
What happened with Carmichael's visit?

01:22:30.000 --> 01:22:34.000
Oh, he was just dropping in on his way to New York,

01:22:34.000 --> 01:22:36.000
or somewhere from the side.

01:22:36.000 --> 01:22:38.000
And it was about three o'clock in the morning.

01:22:38.000 --> 01:22:40.000
He came up and rang the bell.

01:22:40.000 --> 01:22:43.000
Branch was downstairs sleeping on the couch.

01:22:43.000 --> 01:22:46.000
Well, the gun was stuck behind and got...

01:22:46.000 --> 01:22:48.000
So he grabbed the gun and got up now.

01:22:48.000 --> 01:22:51.000
Now, since I found out about his connection with FBI,

01:22:51.000 --> 01:22:54.000
I don't know whether that was some fake thing,

01:22:54.000 --> 01:22:58.000
or whether it was a natural instinct or fear or whatever.

01:22:58.000 --> 01:23:03.000
But it was a little, you know, little upset for a five-minute.

01:23:03.000 --> 01:23:05.000
Yeah, yeah.

01:23:05.000 --> 01:23:10.000
How did you see the resolution to that very, very active phase,

01:23:10.000 --> 01:23:15.000
6263 into 64 in Cambridge?

01:23:15.000 --> 01:23:20.000
What was your sense of what you'd accomplished?

01:23:20.000 --> 01:23:25.000
I thought we had accomplished what we wanted.

01:23:25.000 --> 01:23:27.000
I have...

01:23:27.000 --> 01:23:30.000
I may have made a mistake.

01:23:30.000 --> 01:23:35.000
There was a space of time after I left that I didn't understand

01:23:35.000 --> 01:23:36.000
why they were...

01:23:36.000 --> 01:23:38.000
It seems like the SNCC people left there

01:23:38.000 --> 01:23:41.000
went to the Latin City ahead of the demonstration.

01:23:41.000 --> 01:23:43.000
And they were asking for help.

01:23:43.000 --> 01:23:44.000
And I didn't...

01:23:44.000 --> 01:23:48.000
In reading it in retrospect, I didn't understand it.

01:23:48.000 --> 01:23:50.000
And I didn't understand what was going on.

01:23:50.000 --> 01:23:52.000
But apparently, it rioted itself,

01:23:52.000 --> 01:23:55.000
and they just segregated the schools.

01:23:55.000 --> 01:23:57.000
And they...

01:23:57.000 --> 01:24:00.000
It started a housing project and stuff.

01:24:00.000 --> 01:24:02.000
What it seems to be...

01:24:02.000 --> 01:24:03.000
I look back...

01:24:03.000 --> 01:24:06.000
It seems to be like six or seven months

01:24:06.000 --> 01:24:09.000
when something should have been happening.

01:24:09.000 --> 01:24:17.000
And I just don't know whether that was incompetence or...

01:24:17.000 --> 01:24:19.000
Or...

01:24:19.000 --> 01:24:20.000
Or what.

01:24:20.000 --> 01:24:24.000
But I did think that as it moved forward,

01:24:24.000 --> 01:24:27.000
that it would make a difference.

01:24:27.000 --> 01:24:29.000
In terms of white Cambridge,

01:24:29.000 --> 01:24:32.000
I think maybe...

01:24:32.000 --> 01:24:35.000
Some of it went extremely racist

01:24:35.000 --> 01:24:39.000
to a Justice County County.

01:24:39.000 --> 01:24:41.000
Elected Lemieux...

01:24:41.000 --> 01:24:42.000
Elected...

01:24:42.000 --> 01:24:46.000
Lemieux Chester on the county hands.

01:24:46.000 --> 01:24:51.000
Um...

01:24:51.000 --> 01:24:54.000
They...

01:24:54.000 --> 01:24:58.000
They at some point, the man here at the orphan's court,

01:24:58.000 --> 01:25:01.000
so they began to make steps

01:25:01.000 --> 01:25:05.000
in some of their structures.

01:25:05.000 --> 01:25:08.000
Um...

01:25:08.000 --> 01:25:11.000
And then, of course, that desegregation

01:25:11.000 --> 01:25:15.000
of the busing systems and stuff.

01:25:15.000 --> 01:25:18.000
Now, as I said, when I went back the other day,

01:25:18.000 --> 01:25:23.000
now they amazingly have a black woman mayor.

01:25:23.000 --> 01:25:26.000
Her father was on my executive board.

01:25:26.000 --> 01:25:29.000
In fact, in that picture with the gun,

01:25:29.000 --> 01:25:32.000
where they were getting ready to stab me,

01:25:32.000 --> 01:25:36.000
he's the guy who's back as to the camera.

01:25:36.000 --> 01:25:39.000
That's when National Guardsman has a rifle in your place.

01:25:39.000 --> 01:25:40.000
Yes, yeah.

01:25:40.000 --> 01:25:41.000
And you're pushing it in?

01:25:41.000 --> 01:25:42.000
Yes.

01:25:42.000 --> 01:25:45.000
I think he was going to try and stab me from behind.

01:25:45.000 --> 01:25:47.000
But anyhow...

01:25:47.000 --> 01:25:49.000
And that was a time when...

01:25:49.000 --> 01:25:52.000
when Gelton was trying to argue me out

01:25:52.000 --> 01:25:56.000
of having a demonstration and these pow, pow, pow, pow.

01:25:56.000 --> 01:25:57.000
I didn't know it was...

01:25:57.000 --> 01:26:00.000
We both, I think, thought it was guns.

01:26:00.000 --> 01:26:02.000
But it proved it was tear gas.

01:26:02.000 --> 01:26:05.000
But it was in that excitement.

01:26:05.000 --> 01:26:07.000
Yeah.

01:26:07.000 --> 01:26:09.000
So...

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:11.000
Let me ask this.

01:26:11.000 --> 01:26:13.000
What were your motives, all of your motives,

01:26:13.000 --> 01:26:17.000
in moving to New York City, 65?

01:26:17.000 --> 01:26:20.000
Oh, because my husband lived in New York.

01:26:20.000 --> 01:26:23.000
I mean, the guy I married, the dude.

01:26:23.000 --> 01:26:26.000
Well, we had signed the agreement.

01:26:26.000 --> 01:26:32.000
There was... there was leadership left there.

01:26:32.000 --> 01:26:39.000
And I had two girls that had to go to school and be raised.

01:26:40.000 --> 01:26:43.000
I remember this was not a paid position.

01:26:43.000 --> 01:26:50.000
This was not an organization in a sense of salaries and office

01:26:50.000 --> 01:26:52.000
and secretaries and stuff.

01:26:52.000 --> 01:26:56.000
All the weird people that volunteered for some of that stuff.

01:26:56.000 --> 01:27:04.000
So this did not expend the rest of my life doing it.

01:27:04.000 --> 01:27:11.000
And so that hopefully had accomplished something.

01:27:11.000 --> 01:27:15.000
And if nothing else, the people found out that they could

01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:18.000
at least fight against it.

01:27:18.000 --> 01:27:21.000
They decided to.

01:27:21.000 --> 01:27:25.000
Tell me, the last thing I want to ask about is the last question is,

01:27:25.000 --> 01:27:30.000
that there was an event in Cambridge for you a few years ago.

01:27:30.000 --> 01:27:34.000
And I'd love to have you just recall that experience.

01:27:34.000 --> 01:27:36.000
Oh, you mean when they said...

01:27:36.000 --> 01:27:40.000
Oh, I thought it was simply amazing.

01:27:40.000 --> 01:27:44.000
It was beyond my expectations.

01:27:44.000 --> 01:27:53.000
The people who arranged it were very young at that time.

01:27:53.000 --> 01:27:59.000
I didn't know where the idea came from or why.

01:27:59.000 --> 01:28:03.000
But it amazed me that the whole town was involved.

01:28:03.000 --> 01:28:05.000
Not just that, I remember.

01:28:05.000 --> 01:28:09.000
Oh, yeah, no, that's what I mean when I say the whole town was involved.

01:28:09.000 --> 01:28:13.000
I didn't realize that when I accepted it.

01:28:13.000 --> 01:28:17.000
But once I started on that day through this service,

01:28:17.000 --> 01:28:19.000
I really overwhelmed me.

01:28:19.000 --> 01:28:24.000
And as I said, when I got to the banquet at Elk's home that night.

01:28:24.000 --> 01:28:26.000
And got up to make the speech.

01:28:26.000 --> 01:28:30.000
I thought mainly probably from expo, and people and stuff.

01:28:30.000 --> 01:28:32.000
I saw the mixed audience.

01:28:32.000 --> 01:28:36.000
I thought, oh my god, I can't have to speak to everybody.

01:28:36.000 --> 01:28:39.000
So then I just said to kind of make your stuff.

01:28:39.000 --> 01:28:41.000
I don't even know what it was I said now.

01:28:41.000 --> 01:28:42.000
But it was overwhelming.

01:28:42.000 --> 01:28:49.000
And then the awards came from all kinds of people in government.

01:28:49.000 --> 01:28:52.000
Which, you know, I did not expect.

01:28:52.000 --> 01:28:57.000
And then of course, the new mayor had just been elected.

01:28:57.000 --> 01:29:01.000
It was just like overwhelming.

01:29:01.000 --> 01:29:07.000
I had been earlier, was that earlier?

01:29:07.000 --> 01:29:10.000
The thing at Washington College.

01:29:10.000 --> 01:29:13.000
I'm not certain of those dates.

01:29:13.000 --> 01:29:15.000
I remember spec I'm not too.

01:29:15.000 --> 01:29:17.000
But I was surprised at that.

01:29:18.000 --> 01:29:21.000
And the only reason why I accepted that is because one,

01:29:21.000 --> 01:29:24.000
it was on the East and Shore 2, did not ever, had not ever

01:29:24.000 --> 01:29:26.000
remember hearing about it.

01:29:26.000 --> 01:29:29.000
And because the president said he had learned about Cambridge,

01:29:29.000 --> 01:29:33.000
by listening to Malcolm X's grassroots views.

01:29:33.000 --> 01:29:36.000
So I thought that was interesting.

01:29:36.000 --> 01:29:40.000
And it was.

01:29:40.000 --> 01:29:46.000
But as I told Bertipson, if I had known they were there in the 60s,

01:29:46.000 --> 01:29:49.000
we would have been down there.

01:29:49.000 --> 01:29:54.000
A private, what is it, the fourth school in the country

01:29:54.000 --> 01:30:03.000
of a class school or all right, on the East and Shore Mall?

01:30:03.000 --> 01:30:08.000
I used to go to Chesterton with my cousin while he played poker

01:30:08.000 --> 01:30:10.000
with Lloyd Price and stuff.

01:30:10.000 --> 01:30:13.000
And the guy, all these bands and things would come through

01:30:13.000 --> 01:30:19.000
and had no idea that anything like that existed,

01:30:19.000 --> 01:30:22.000
it just did that.

01:30:22.000 --> 01:30:28.000
And when I got there, I found that they give a certain percentage

01:30:28.000 --> 01:30:32.000
of scholarships now to those kids that come out of high school

01:30:32.000 --> 01:30:35.000
in Penn County.

01:30:40.000 --> 01:30:42.000
Any final thoughts?

01:30:42.000 --> 01:30:46.000
No, I think this country is going to hell in the hand basket,

01:30:46.000 --> 01:30:49.000
but other than that.

01:30:49.000 --> 01:30:51.000
What makes you discouraged?

01:30:51.000 --> 01:30:53.000
I know there are many things that might be on that list.

01:30:53.000 --> 01:30:57.000
Well, I think that there's extremely right wing and fastest

01:30:57.000 --> 01:30:58.000
Supreme Court.

01:30:58.000 --> 01:31:02.000
And I'm saying that after considering slavery and the position

01:31:02.000 --> 01:31:03.000
on that.

01:31:03.000 --> 01:31:08.000
But I think now that stuff they've gotten away with with blacks,

01:31:08.000 --> 01:31:11.000
they're getting away with it every party of blacks and whites.

01:31:12.000 --> 01:31:15.000
I don't think some whites, especially immigrants.

01:31:15.000 --> 01:31:19.000
I just had an argument yesterday with a couple of my citizenship

01:31:19.000 --> 01:31:20.000
class.

01:31:20.000 --> 01:31:24.000
They said, why are they doing, you know, you better be aware

01:31:24.000 --> 01:31:25.000
of what they're doing.

01:31:25.000 --> 01:31:29.000
I think the Republicans are not just right wing Republicans.

01:31:29.000 --> 01:31:32.000
I think they're fastest Republicans.

01:31:32.000 --> 01:31:36.000
If they get away with this, you know, all people in this country

01:31:36.000 --> 01:31:38.000
are going to have a time.

01:31:42.000 --> 01:31:44.000
And I don't know.

01:31:44.000 --> 01:31:47.000
I mean, I watch.

01:31:47.000 --> 01:31:56.000
And I think it's because in Egypt, I still, all those people

01:31:56.000 --> 01:32:00.000
I've missed, that rapport that I watch.

01:32:00.000 --> 01:32:06.000
I don't understand why with some of this except for the T-Poli.

01:32:06.000 --> 01:32:09.000
But I think they used to organize and parental was like,

01:32:09.000 --> 01:32:10.000
that's snicked it.

01:32:10.000 --> 01:32:12.000
And they let them get too far out there.

01:32:12.000 --> 01:32:15.000
But there's no opposing entity.

01:32:19.000 --> 01:32:24.000
Well, unless it's an academia, but I can't imagine just people

01:32:24.000 --> 01:32:26.000
in the country.

01:32:26.000 --> 01:32:28.000
Maybe they don't believe it.

01:32:31.000 --> 01:32:36.000
Mr. Anjai, I'm very grateful for your sharing all this great

01:32:36.000 --> 01:32:39.000
history and your perspective for the series.

01:32:39.000 --> 01:32:42.000
And it's been a real pleasure and a privilege to be with you.

01:32:42.000 --> 01:32:43.000
Thank you so much.

01:32:43.000 --> 01:32:44.000
Oh, you're certainly welcome.

01:32:44.000 --> 01:32:47.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress

01:32:47.000 --> 01:32:51.000
and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History

01:32:51.000 --> 01:32:52.000
and Culture.

